 model with an\ninternal temperature of ~1100 K, which may be related to the inflated radius.\nThe difference between the TESS and Spitzer brightness temperatures can be\nexplained by stronger molecular opacity in the Spitzer bands. On the night\nside, this opacity is due primarily to CH4 and CO while on the day side it is\ndue to H2-H2 and H2-He collision-induced absorption.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 17 Jun 2020 09:46:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 15 Mar 2021 09:31:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-04-21"}
